1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,800
 So now we're going to talk about JavaScript

2
00:00:01,800 --> 00:00:03,000
 as a programming language.

3
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:05,240
 Now we're just going to talk about the syntax.

4
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:07,560
 So we'll start out, say, with comments.

5
00:00:07,560 --> 00:00:09,720
 So I love the comments in JavaScript.

6
00:00:09,720 --> 00:00:11,300
 There are two kinds of comments, and they

7
00:00:11,300 --> 00:00:14,720
 have to do with what languages did the influencing.

8
00:00:14,720 --> 00:00:20,120
 And so the slash star, star slash, is a multi-line comment.

9
00:00:20,120 --> 00:00:24,640
 So this is all comment from here all the way to here.

10
00:00:24,640 --> 00:00:25,680
 And you can have new lines.

11
00:00:25,680 --> 00:00:28,000
 This is great for writing documentation.

12
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:30,080
 That comes from the C language.

13
00:00:30,080 --> 00:00:32,160
 Java also supports it as well.

14
00:00:32,160 --> 00:00:35,700
 And then the C++ language has slash slash

15
00:00:35,700 --> 00:00:37,040
 to the end of the line.

16
00:00:37,040 --> 00:00:40,640
 That's much more like the pound sign comment in Python.

17
00:00:40,640 --> 00:00:43,120
 But I like both of those styles.

18
00:00:43,120 --> 00:00:45,620
 I like using these for documentation sections,

19
00:00:45,620 --> 00:00:47,600
 and I like these for short comments.

20
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:49,020
 So nice.

21
00:00:49,020 --> 00:00:50,320
 Thank you very much.

22
00:00:50,320 --> 00:00:53,760
 White space and new lines do not matter.

23
00:00:53,760 --> 00:00:55,480
 Statements end in a semicolon.

24
00:00:55,480 --> 00:00:58,720
 It turns out that that's not technically true.

25
00:00:58,720 --> 00:01:02,000
 But if you just pretend that all statements end in a semicolon,

26
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,280
 then if you move to Java, or C++, or C, or PHP,

27
00:01:07,280 --> 00:01:09,040
 then you're not like, oh, when do

28
00:01:09,040 --> 00:01:10,500
 I have to put the semicolon on?

29
00:01:10,500 --> 00:01:11,480
 Well, in those languages, you have

30
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:12,960
 to put it on just about everywhere.

31
00:01:12,960 --> 00:01:15,440
 So just put semicolons at the end of every line,

32
00:01:15,440 --> 00:01:17,480
 and you can just pretend you're writing C.

33
00:01:17,480 --> 00:01:19,440
 And then when you get to C, you'll be like, oh, this

34
00:01:19,440 --> 00:01:21,960
 is just like JavaScript, even though under the--

35
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:24,600
 on the implementation, it's very different, very, very

36
00:01:24,600 --> 00:01:25,720
 different.

37
00:01:25,720 --> 00:01:29,280
 So here is just an example of some really nasty JavaScript

38
00:01:29,280 --> 00:01:34,040
 where x equals 3 plus 5 times 4 on two lines,

39
00:01:34,040 --> 00:01:37,240
 and then this line's jammed up and console.log.

40
00:01:37,240 --> 00:01:38,120
 That's OK.

41
00:01:38,120 --> 00:01:41,000
 It just doesn't matter.

42
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:43,120
 JavaScript and these C-style languages

43
00:01:43,120 --> 00:01:45,520
 just don't care what the white space is.

44
00:01:45,520 --> 00:01:48,360
 They're looking for characters.

45
00:01:48,360 --> 00:01:51,000
 Blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, semicolon.

46
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:52,040
 That must be the end of the line.

47
00:01:52,040 --> 00:01:54,280
 Blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, semicolon.

48
00:01:54,280 --> 00:01:55,560
 That's the end of the line.

49
00:01:55,560 --> 00:01:59,280
 So just the new line is just like another space-like character

50
00:01:59,280 --> 00:02:04,520
 ultimately in these languages.

51
00:02:04,520 --> 00:02:07,440
 Variable names are kind of normal.

52
00:02:07,440 --> 00:02:09,520
 They can start with letters.

53
00:02:09,520 --> 00:02:13,560
 I mean, they're letters and numbers and underscore

54
00:02:13,560 --> 00:02:15,560
 and dollar sign, but they're not supposed

55
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:18,120
 to start with a number, and they are case sensitive.

56
00:02:18,120 --> 00:02:20,920
 Just please-- we use case sometimes

57
00:02:20,920 --> 00:02:23,560
 as a signal because different kinds of variables

58
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:28,040
 we like either camel case them or all uppercase.

59
00:02:28,040 --> 00:02:32,000
 I use case to signal things.

60
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:38,880
 And it turns out that because JavaScript sort of saw

61
00:02:38,880 --> 00:02:41,280
 what PHP and Perl looked like, they

62
00:02:41,280 --> 00:02:43,440
 allowed dollar signs at the beginning variables

63
00:02:43,440 --> 00:02:45,160
 because PHP and Perl are the places

64
00:02:45,160 --> 00:02:47,000
 where dollar signs are allowed.

65
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,760
 But when people started writing JavaScript,

66
00:02:50,760 --> 00:02:53,360
 they wanted to be more like Java.

67
00:02:53,360 --> 00:02:55,440
 Java doesn't allow dollar signs in variables.

68
00:02:55,440 --> 00:02:58,840
 And so there was kind of like this unwritten rule, which

69
00:02:58,840 --> 00:03:03,000
 we will come back to, just don't start a variable with dollar

70
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:05,080
 sign, even though JavaScript allows it.

71
00:03:05,080 --> 00:03:06,200
 Just kind of don't do it.

72
00:03:06,200 --> 00:03:08,080
 It's not cool.

73
00:03:08,080 --> 00:03:12,960
 String constants, single quotes and double quotes

74
00:03:12,960 --> 00:03:15,000
 function the exact same way.

75
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:18,200
 I like that a lot.

76
00:03:18,200 --> 00:03:22,000
 Stylistically, what I tend to do is I tend to use single quotes

77
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,800
 as much as I can in JavaScript because ultimately,

78
00:03:25,800 --> 00:03:27,760
 double quotes are part of HTML.

79
00:03:27,760 --> 00:03:30,160
 And when I'm mixing my HTML in JavaScript,

80
00:03:30,160 --> 00:03:31,760
 I tend to want to look at it and say

81
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:35,480
 that single quote is a JavaScript quote versus a HTML

82
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:36,040
 quote.

83
00:03:36,040 --> 00:03:37,740
 So if we take a look at this little code,

84
00:03:37,740 --> 00:03:40,320
 you see like this text equal JavaScript,

85
00:03:40,320 --> 00:03:41,600
 that's in double quotes.

86
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:42,960
 And it has to be.

87
00:03:42,960 --> 00:03:46,400
 So the one line and two line, I could use single quotes

88
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:47,760
 or double quotes for that.

89
00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:50,240
 But for me, I try to use single quotes

90
00:03:50,240 --> 00:03:52,800
 as much as possible when I'm in JavaScript.

91
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:56,720
 So I can take a look at this code and know HTML JavaScript.

92
00:03:56,720 --> 00:03:59,600
 If I'm in double quotes, I'm generally dealing with HTML.

93
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:03,280
 And because JavaScript is sometimes writing HTML,

94
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:06,200
 it's writing double quotes into the document

95
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:09,640
 because it has to because that's how HTML requires it.

96
00:04:09,640 --> 00:04:11,380
 So I have a single quote string that

97
00:04:11,380 --> 00:04:12,840
 has a double quote in the middle of it

98
00:04:12,840 --> 00:04:15,280
 because I'm writing HTML in JavaScript.

99
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:16,760
 That'll make more sense to you later.

100
00:04:16,760 --> 00:04:19,520
 So you can do either one, and you'll

101
00:04:19,520 --> 00:04:22,480
 see examples where JavaScript just uses double quotes.

102
00:04:22,480 --> 00:04:27,040
 But I prefer single quotes as much as I possibly can.

103
00:04:27,040 --> 00:04:29,000
 Unumeric constants are pretty much

104
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:37,120
 like every other language, but there is only one number type.

105
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:39,800
 In most languages, there's like an integer and a floating

106
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:41,400
 point.

107
00:04:41,400 --> 00:04:43,440
 Sometimes there's double and float.

108
00:04:43,440 --> 00:04:46,840
 There's different kinds of long integers.

109
00:04:46,840 --> 00:04:50,280
 In JavaScript, I think in a way they were smart.

110
00:04:50,280 --> 00:04:53,680
 And they basically made one type, one numeric type

111
00:04:53,680 --> 00:04:55,080
 called number.

112
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:57,560
 And so for example, if you take 5/3,

113
00:04:57,560 --> 00:05:01,920
 that is a floating point number, 1.666 repeating forever.

114
00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:04,520
 If you want to turn that into an integer,

115
00:05:04,520 --> 00:05:07,280
 you just truncate it like math.trunc.

116
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:10,040
 Math is a library that's in JavaScript.

117
00:05:10,040 --> 00:05:14,000
 Now when you get back an x, it's still a floating point number.

118
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:15,720
 It just is shown as an integer because you've

119
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:18,720
 chopped off the decimal part.

120
00:05:18,720 --> 00:05:21,720
 And so you have to be careful because they're really

121
00:05:21,720 --> 00:05:23,200
 floating point numbers.

122
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:26,280
 Every one of them, some of them are shown as integers

123
00:05:26,280 --> 00:05:27,280
 when you print them out.

124
00:05:27,280 --> 00:05:32,280
 But in general, there are no integers in JavaScript.

125
00:05:32,280 --> 00:05:35,200
 So there's a whole bunch of operators, plus, minus,

126
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:39,440
 multiply, divide, truncate.

127
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:42,080
 Those are pretty much like every other programming language.

128
00:05:42,080 --> 00:05:48,840
 More operators like the modulo operator.

129
00:05:48,840 --> 00:05:51,880
 Modulo operator is the percent sign.

130
00:05:51,880 --> 00:05:53,800
 And that is the remainder operator.

131
00:05:53,800 --> 00:05:59,680
 So 45 divided by 7 is 6 remainder 3.

132
00:05:59,680 --> 00:06:09,560
 And that remainder, 45, 7 is 6, 42, 3, remainder 3.

133
00:06:09,560 --> 00:06:11,600
 That 3 is what goes there.

134
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:16,960
 So division with truncation will give you the 6,

135
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:19,480
 but the remainder will give you the 3.

136
00:06:19,480 --> 00:06:22,440
 And it turns out that that modulo is really quite useful.

137
00:06:22,440 --> 00:06:26,720
 Like if you want to do something every 100th time

138
00:06:26,720 --> 00:06:29,800
 through an iteration, you take the iteration counter,

139
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:30,960
 like 1, 2, 3.

140
00:06:30,960 --> 00:06:34,480
 And if you modulo 100 and the result is 0, remainder 0,

141
00:06:34,480 --> 00:06:36,400
 it's an even multiple of 100.

142
00:06:36,400 --> 00:06:38,680
 And that means every 100 times you can do something.

143
00:06:38,680 --> 00:06:42,600
 So we like modulo.

144
00:06:42,600 --> 00:06:46,040
 There are side effect operators.

145
00:06:46,040 --> 00:06:47,520
 Oops, come back.

146
00:06:47,520 --> 00:06:49,280
 There are side effect operators.

147
00:06:49,280 --> 00:06:54,960
 K++ says, retrieve K, have it be part of an expression perhaps,

148
00:06:54,960 --> 00:06:57,080
 then add 1 to it, store it back down.

149
00:06:57,080 --> 00:07:00,320
 So if I say K++, it says 3.

150
00:07:00,320 --> 00:07:02,560
 But then afterwards, K has become 4.

151
00:07:02,560 --> 00:07:04,960
 So after it retrieved the K and printed it,

152
00:07:04,960 --> 00:07:08,200
 then it turned it into 4.

153
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:10,880
 There's very few places that we actually use these.

154
00:07:10,880 --> 00:07:12,280
 And then we use them all the time.

155
00:07:12,280 --> 00:07:15,480
 But in general, you can hurt yourself

156
00:07:15,480 --> 00:07:17,240
 if you write too much of this stuff.

157
00:07:17,240 --> 00:07:20,680
 There is a pre-increment, minus, minus K.

158
00:07:20,680 --> 00:07:25,120
 And that says, subtract 1 from K, and then print it out,

159
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:26,280
 which is 3.

160
00:07:26,280 --> 00:07:30,040
 And then the 3 goes back into K.

161
00:07:30,040 --> 00:07:34,080
 Then there are some side effect operators.

162
00:07:34,080 --> 00:07:38,520
 J plus equals is the same as J equals J plus 5.

163
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:42,720
 And the same is true for all these things.

164
00:07:42,720 --> 00:07:47,560
 Actually, that's a typo there, slash equals.

165
00:07:47,560 --> 00:07:51,720
 And so most people do not use these formats.

166
00:07:51,720 --> 00:07:54,400
 I just show them to you in case you ever see some code.

167
00:07:54,400 --> 00:07:57,040
 I always prefer to write my increments and decrements

168
00:07:57,040 --> 00:07:59,040
 and divisions out.

169
00:07:59,040 --> 00:08:02,440
 It's not particularly faster that way.

170
00:08:02,440 --> 00:08:04,200
 It's just a syntax.

171
00:08:04,200 --> 00:08:07,720
 This comes from C. All of these fancy bits

172
00:08:07,720 --> 00:08:09,280
 come from the C language.

173
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:13,480
 And JavaScript was just-- and Java do the same thing.

174
00:08:13,480 --> 00:08:17,360
 And so those two languages are represented here.

175
00:08:17,360 --> 00:08:19,880
 And so that's why these operators are here.

176
00:08:19,880 --> 00:08:22,080
 Comparison operators.

177
00:08:22,080 --> 00:08:25,840
 All C-style languages, one of the trickiest things

178
00:08:25,840 --> 00:08:28,680
 you've got to realize is that the single equal sign

179
00:08:28,680 --> 00:08:29,960
 is an assignment statement.

180
00:08:29,960 --> 00:08:32,120
 And I like to think of that as changing.

181
00:08:32,120 --> 00:08:35,880
 So the 10 is being stored into the J. To say,

182
00:08:35,880 --> 00:08:37,120
 is J equal to 10?

183
00:08:37,120 --> 00:08:38,960
 This is like a question mark.

184
00:08:38,960 --> 00:08:41,920
 I wish this was like question equals.

185
00:08:41,920 --> 00:08:43,920
 That would be like, is it equal to?

186
00:08:43,920 --> 00:08:45,360
 But that's not what they do.

187
00:08:45,360 --> 00:08:47,600
 They decided double equals was the one that

188
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:48,480
 was the question mark.

189
00:08:48,480 --> 00:08:51,560
 And that's asking the question, is J equal to 10?

190
00:08:51,560 --> 00:08:53,960
 And it returns a true or a false when it's evaluated.

191
00:08:53,960 --> 00:08:55,720
 So J equals 10 is true.

192
00:08:55,720 --> 00:08:57,120
 J not equal 17.

193
00:08:57,120 --> 00:08:59,400
 That's exclamation equal.

194
00:08:59,400 --> 00:09:01,440
 Again, I wish this was question mark equal.

195
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:04,880
 But that's-- going back to 1972, I had to catch them and say,

196
00:09:04,880 --> 00:09:06,080
 no, don't make double equals.

197
00:09:06,080 --> 00:09:08,200
 Make question equal.

198
00:09:08,200 --> 00:09:13,440
 Not equal, less than, greater than, less than or equal to.

199
00:09:13,440 --> 00:09:16,600
 Now, there's a special operator.

200
00:09:16,600 --> 00:09:21,160
 And you see this in Python in the is and is not operator.

201
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:24,920
 So the double equals is a comparison

202
00:09:24,920 --> 00:09:27,040
 with type conversion.

203
00:09:27,040 --> 00:09:31,240
 So it says, can the left side of the double equals, the J,

204
00:09:31,240 --> 00:09:35,560
 be converted eventually to become equal to 0?

205
00:09:35,560 --> 00:09:40,000
 And so in this particular case, J is false.

206
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:43,600
 So it is of type Boolean.

207
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:46,560
 But a false can be coerced into 0.

208
00:09:46,560 --> 00:09:50,760
 So false is equal to 0 with some conversion.

209
00:09:50,760 --> 00:09:58,760
 But then, if we want to compare two things in terms of both

210
00:09:58,760 --> 00:10:02,920
 their type and their value with no implicit type conversion,

211
00:10:02,920 --> 00:10:06,400
 if I say, is J triple equals 0?

212
00:10:06,400 --> 00:10:12,160
 That says, is J the same type as 0, which is a number,

213
00:10:12,160 --> 00:10:13,560
 and has the same value?

214
00:10:13,560 --> 00:10:16,440
 Well, J is a Boolean, because it's true or false.

215
00:10:16,440 --> 00:10:18,400
 And so this turns out to be false.

216
00:10:18,400 --> 00:10:22,320
 So J is not triple equals.

217
00:10:22,320 --> 00:10:24,040
 And J is not triple equals true.

218
00:10:24,040 --> 00:10:26,440
 And so you have triple equals and not--

219
00:10:26,440 --> 00:10:29,440
 it's like not equal equal, but I call it not triple equals.

220
00:10:29,440 --> 00:10:34,760
 So there's a whole series of logical operators,

221
00:10:34,760 --> 00:10:39,480
 much like that, that return for you true and falses.

222
00:10:39,480 --> 00:10:41,360
 And so we've got our greater than.

223
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:45,600
 So we've got double ampersand, which is and.

224
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:48,160
 So for the whole operation, for the whole expression

225
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:50,520
 to be true, both sides have to be true.

226
00:10:50,520 --> 00:10:53,720
 So is K greater than 1 and J less than 10?

227
00:10:53,720 --> 00:10:56,160
 And in this case, the answer is yes.

228
00:10:56,160 --> 00:10:58,240
 Is K greater than 10?

229
00:10:58,240 --> 00:10:59,080
 No.

230
00:10:59,080 --> 00:11:00,880
 And is J greater than 10?

231
00:11:00,880 --> 00:11:03,240
 So that's true, but this one's false.

232
00:11:03,240 --> 00:11:06,560
 False and true become false.

233
00:11:06,560 --> 00:11:10,640
 Or is K greater than 10 or J greater than 10?

234
00:11:10,640 --> 00:11:14,640
 No, neither are true, so the result is false.

235
00:11:14,640 --> 00:11:17,240
 And then there is a unary not operator

236
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:18,680
 that you can put in front.

237
00:11:18,680 --> 00:11:21,560
 That's like saying K greater than 10, well, that's false.

238
00:11:21,560 --> 00:11:26,200
 But then if I apply a not to it, it becomes true.

239
00:11:26,200 --> 00:11:29,600
 String concatenation is a little different than Python.

240
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:34,560
 It uses the plus operator, but it will convert things

241
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:35,640
 to string, right?

242
00:11:35,640 --> 00:11:40,280
 So X equals 12 is a number, and I'm adding a number

243
00:11:40,280 --> 00:11:42,760
 to a string, and it's like, meh, I'll convert that

244
00:11:42,760 --> 00:11:45,480
 into a string, and so that 12 becomes a string,

245
00:11:45,480 --> 00:11:47,680
 and you end up with a string that's hello 12 people

246
00:11:47,680 --> 00:11:49,920
 with one, two characters.

247
00:11:49,920 --> 00:11:52,080
 The number 12 is long gone at that point.

248
00:11:52,080 --> 00:11:53,760
 So there is a conversion.

249
00:11:53,760 --> 00:11:55,440
 Normally, if this were in Python,

250
00:11:55,440 --> 00:11:59,000
 you'd say str parentheses to force it to a string.

251
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:02,280
 The plus is smart enough to automatically convert it.

252
00:12:02,280 --> 00:12:04,720
 You can debate which of those things you prefer,

253
00:12:04,720 --> 00:12:08,720
 and I can come down on either side of it.

254
00:12:08,720 --> 00:12:10,880
 There is something to respect about Python

255
00:12:10,880 --> 00:12:13,000
 that basically says if you want it to be a string,

256
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:15,200
 you as the programmer should say it.

257
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:17,680
 Languages that are sort of loosey-goosey

258
00:12:17,680 --> 00:12:19,840
 that do things to make it most convenient,

259
00:12:19,840 --> 00:12:22,760
 like PHP and JavaScript, sometimes can get you

260
00:12:22,760 --> 00:12:27,760
 into a trouble, and this is where you can always tell

261
00:12:29,080 --> 00:12:29,920
 NaN.

262
00:12:29,920 --> 00:12:32,760
 If you see NaN in a user interface anywhere in the web,

263
00:12:32,760 --> 00:12:35,400
 you're like, oh, somebody did a JavaScript calculation

264
00:12:35,400 --> 00:12:39,000
 just like this, and something went wrong,

265
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:44,000
 'cause that's what happens when additions go wrong.

266
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:46,720
 We'll see that in a second.

267
00:12:46,720 --> 00:12:50,960
 So variable typing is a little confusing

268
00:12:50,960 --> 00:12:53,120
 because we're using plus.

269
00:12:53,120 --> 00:12:54,760
 Sometimes we're using it for concatenation.

270
00:12:54,760 --> 00:12:56,920
 Sometimes we're using it for addition.

271
00:12:56,920 --> 00:12:59,060
 So in this particular case where we take the string

272
00:12:59,060 --> 00:13:00,760
 one, two, three, and add 10 to it,

273
00:13:00,760 --> 00:13:04,280
 it sees that as a concatenation and gives us back a string.

274
00:13:04,280 --> 00:13:07,400
 But if we say the string one, two, three times one,

275
00:13:07,400 --> 00:13:11,160
 then it converts that to an integer times one,

276
00:13:11,160 --> 00:13:12,160
 and that's 10.

277
00:13:12,160 --> 00:13:15,880
 So it becomes 133, but that is a number.

278
00:13:15,880 --> 00:13:17,320
 But what happens if we take something

279
00:13:17,320 --> 00:13:18,560
 that's not even a number?

280
00:13:18,560 --> 00:13:21,560
 Well, multiply it by one.

281
00:13:21,560 --> 00:13:24,120
 That is not a number.

282
00:13:24,120 --> 00:13:26,440
 And then we add 10 to it, and it's still not a number,

283
00:13:26,440 --> 00:13:27,960
 and this is not a number.

284
00:13:27,960 --> 00:13:31,480
 And that's why you see nan on all these webpages,

285
00:13:31,480 --> 00:13:35,000
 like percent complete, nan.

286
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:36,880
 And that's because it was adding one

287
00:13:36,880 --> 00:13:39,520
 to something like a fault that wasn't a number

288
00:13:39,520 --> 00:13:40,920
 and couldn't be conversed into a number,

289
00:13:40,920 --> 00:13:42,220
 like a string or something.

290
00:13:42,220 --> 00:13:46,320
 And once you get something that's a nan,

291
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:49,240
 it's very, very, very sticky.

292
00:13:49,240 --> 00:13:50,640
 But it doesn't blow up.

293
00:13:50,640 --> 00:13:52,800
 It just keeps running and shows you nan

294
00:13:52,800 --> 00:13:54,120
 in your user interface.

295
00:13:55,520 --> 00:13:58,240
 So if a string can't be converted

296
00:13:58,240 --> 00:14:02,280
 because of mathematical operation, you get a nan.

297
00:14:02,280 --> 00:14:04,600
 There is a function called isnan

298
00:14:04,600 --> 00:14:07,720
 that gives you a true/false, like is there a nan?

299
00:14:07,720 --> 00:14:08,960
 Nan is a value.

300
00:14:08,960 --> 00:14:10,760
 It's not the lack of a value.

301
00:14:10,760 --> 00:14:14,360
 Something like null would be a lack of a value,

302
00:14:14,360 --> 00:14:17,320
 or empty in Python would be the lack of a value.

303
00:14:17,320 --> 00:14:19,000
 Isnan is an actual value.

304
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:21,720
 It's just like a value that's the indication

305
00:14:21,720 --> 00:14:25,480
 within a number that is, it's a number.

306
00:14:25,480 --> 00:14:28,120
 If you divide by two, you get another value

307
00:14:28,120 --> 00:14:29,400
 that's not really a value.

308
00:14:29,400 --> 00:14:31,720
 It's a special value called infinity.

309
00:14:31,720 --> 00:14:34,120
 And if you like add one to infinity, you still get infinity.

310
00:14:34,120 --> 00:14:36,720
 If you subtract one from infinity, you still get infinity.

311
00:14:36,720 --> 00:14:39,200
 There's no amount of ones that you can subtract

312
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:41,200
 from infinity to get anything less than infinity

313
00:14:41,200 --> 00:14:44,080
 'cause it's like infinity.

314
00:14:44,080 --> 00:14:45,760
 And there's a function called isinfinity

315
00:14:45,760 --> 00:14:47,440
 that lets you know if the variable

316
00:14:47,440 --> 00:14:49,460
 you're working with is infinity.

317
00:14:52,240 --> 00:14:56,640
 So this seems kind of silly,

318
00:14:56,640 --> 00:14:58,320
 but it turns out that in some ways,

319
00:14:58,320 --> 00:15:01,640
 JavaScript has one of the coolest number classes

320
00:15:01,640 --> 00:15:04,920
 because it uses this internal number format

321
00:15:04,920 --> 00:15:09,920
 called IEEE 450 something, 455 or something.

322
00:15:09,920 --> 00:15:13,680
 And it's actually a scientifically thought out,

323
00:15:13,680 --> 00:15:15,960
 really good way to do number calculations.

324
00:15:15,960 --> 00:15:18,760
 And so in some ways, it does a better job

325
00:15:18,760 --> 00:15:20,880
 of flowing point numbers than some other programming

326
00:15:20,880 --> 00:15:24,120
 languages that just kinda do unpredictable things

327
00:15:24,120 --> 00:15:26,840
 at things like infinity and dividing by zero

328
00:15:26,840 --> 00:15:29,760
 or multiplying by an undefined or something.

329
00:15:29,760 --> 00:15:32,280
 So you gotta respect JavaScript

330
00:15:32,280 --> 00:15:37,200
 because they stuck to their guns on numeric calculations

331
00:15:37,200 --> 00:15:38,200
 and they're pure.

332
00:15:38,200 --> 00:15:41,560
 They're the way computer science researchers suggest

333
00:15:41,560 --> 00:15:42,520
 this is the way you do it

334
00:15:42,520 --> 00:15:44,240
 and that's exactly the way you do it.

335
00:15:44,240 --> 00:15:46,200
 Seems a little weird, I make a little fun of it,

336
00:15:46,200 --> 00:15:47,760
 but it's actually pretty cool.

337
00:15:49,160 --> 00:15:51,360
 If you're in an untyped language and you're passed in

338
00:15:51,360 --> 00:15:53,400
 like a variable and you wanna know is this a string

339
00:15:53,400 --> 00:15:55,480
 or is this an array or is this an object,

340
00:15:55,480 --> 00:15:58,360
 there is a unary function,

341
00:15:58,360 --> 00:16:01,360
 which is just takes one parameter type of,

342
00:16:01,360 --> 00:16:04,360
 that's P-I-P-E-O-F, that's the function,

343
00:16:04,360 --> 00:16:07,040
 that's like multiplication or minus sign,

344
00:16:07,040 --> 00:16:10,320
 type of X and that returns a string.

345
00:16:10,320 --> 00:16:12,840
 So type of a number is the string number.

346
00:16:12,840 --> 00:16:16,960
 If we say what is Y, well, the string double Y,

347
00:16:16,960 --> 00:16:19,600
 it's a string and you can ask for a variable

348
00:16:19,600 --> 00:16:23,120
 that doesn't exist yet and that will be undefined.

349
00:16:23,120 --> 00:16:25,000
 And so you can say is this variable defined yet?

350
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:26,160
 Well, it's not defined yet.

351
00:16:26,160 --> 00:16:28,240
 So this is where you're writing code

352
00:16:28,240 --> 00:16:30,800
 and maybe pass the parameter and you don't know what it is

353
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:33,240
 and you say is it a string, is it an array or whatever.

354
00:16:33,240 --> 00:16:36,880
 So it's good to be able in an untyped environment

355
00:16:36,880 --> 00:16:38,840
 to take a variable that you might have been given

356
00:16:38,840 --> 00:16:40,720
 by somebody else and check its type.

357
00:16:40,720 --> 00:16:46,440
 So up next, we're gonna talk about functions and arrays.

